WEBVTT

00:04.098 --> 00:05.039
Good morning, Church.

00:06.621 --> 00:06.881
Good morning.

00:06.901 --> 00:08.223
If you haven't noticed, I'm not Chad.

00:09.544 --> 00:11.346
My name is Amber Parkinson.

00:11.847 --> 00:15.551
I am a member of Rich Wood Church that have been for about two years now.

00:16.332 --> 00:23.200
And if you remember, what Pastor Chad spoke about last week, it was proximity, breeds, empathy.

00:24.562 --> 00:31.570
And so we thought no better way than to learn what that looks like, than to invite

00:31.842 --> 00:40.616
a couple of individuals that have real experience every day in the very vulnerable population of homelessness in Peoria.

00:41.257 --> 00:48.167
And so we have represented here the Dream Center, Pathway Ministries, and the City of Peoria.

00:54.958 --> 01:00.306
And so what we're hoping is that you will be able to listen to

01:00.738 --> 01:16.613
their lived experience every day and working with these populations and walk away with some really practical ways that you can come alongside either these individuals or other vulnerable populations in the city of Peoria so that we can be for the city.

01:18.735 --> 01:30.546
Okay so we're gonna start off and I'll start with you Andy and we can just take a minute who you are, what is your role and how you're involved in ministering to the homelessness in our city.

01:30.626 --> 01:58.802
My name's Andy King, I'm the Executive Director at Dream Center Purea and been there for over 20 years now and we have many different programs within the Dream Center but one of the main ones is our emergency shelter for women and children and so that's really our involvement is looking at that demographic

01:59.874 --> 02:02.658
Yeah, you'll hear a lot more.

02:02.678 --> 02:04.981
This is John.

02:05.001 --> 02:07.605
I'm John Rokey with Pathway Ministries.

02:07.765 --> 02:17.458
We are gospel-centered ministry of mercy that comes alongside hurting folks and walks with them on a pathway from poverty to progress.

02:17.538 --> 02:20.723
And we have two main kind of avenues that that takes.

02:20.843 --> 02:29.074
Our residential ministries where we serve folks that are struggling with homelessness, abuse, addiction.

02:29.282 --> 02:36.551
And on any given night, we serve about 180 men and women in our residential ministries.

02:36.591 --> 02:45.543
And then we also have our community ministries of Empower Life Center and Pathway Counseling where we provide counseling.

02:46.123 --> 02:57.618
And really, again, it's the same walk alongside that path for women and men, women that are struggling with an unwanted pregnancy or women and men struggling with parenting issues or

02:57.730 --> 03:02.236
mental health issues, and so that's who Pathway Ministries is.

03:04.900 --> 03:10.547
My name is Nicole Morrow, so I am the housing coordinator within the Community Development Department at the City of Peoria.

03:11.108 --> 03:19.619
About four years ago, the city created this position, it didn't exist prior, because we realized that it's hard to solve something that you don't talk about.

03:20.380 --> 03:27.730
And so truly thinking about how individuals and families are impacted by their environment,

03:27.874 --> 03:30.577
and the current housing conditions that exist.

03:30.998 --> 03:32.259
And then how can we do better?

03:32.840 --> 03:40.008
And how can we really make this more of a conversation amongst our policymakers to drive home a difference?

03:40.989 --> 03:47.036
Prior to that, I've been working for the Housing Authority, Phoenix Community Development Services, and the United Way.

03:47.156 --> 03:50.800
So always kind of having a hand in housing and housing advocacy.

03:52.803 --> 03:55.826
Hi, my name is Kristi Scofield and I

03:56.034 --> 04:08.828
Don't have much of a voice today, but I am Director of Homeless and Housing for the Dream Center, and I have done this for the past 30 years in one way or another.

04:08.848 --> 04:16.677
I've been involved with these programs because 31 years ago, I was sleeping in my car with my two children.

04:17.378 --> 04:24.786
They were three and four at the time, and so God directed my life and

04:24.898 --> 04:27.741
in that time period and changed it.

04:27.761 --> 04:31.967
And I have been working these programs ever since.

04:34.470 --> 04:34.710
Awesome.

04:41.118 --> 04:43.561
So we're going to have some direct questions for each of these individuals.

04:43.581 --> 04:46.404
And we're going to start off with Nicole first.

04:46.644 --> 04:51.911
From your perspective, how would you describe the current state of homelessness in the city of Peoria?

04:52.932 --> 04:54.674
Yeah, certainly.

04:55.586 --> 04:59.170
And everyone here on this panel knows that I just got picked to answer this question.

05:00.512 --> 05:10.803
So we see homelessness present itself in many different forms, whether that is housing instability and folks trying to not enter into our homeless services.

05:11.765 --> 05:14.327
We have folks that are doubled up.

05:14.408 --> 05:17.111
So they're staying with a family member, they're staying with a friend.

05:18.212 --> 05:23.538
So we don't even necessarily know what they're experiencing because they show up in the places that we are.

05:23.938 --> 05:26.181
We have our folks that are staying in shelter.

05:26.201 --> 05:27.263
So you've heard from dream center.

05:27.283 --> 05:51.058
You've heard from pathways And we have some folks that are unsheltered right there staying outdoors for a multitude of reasons And what we're seeing in the city right is that these numbers are growing It this isn't a new problem, but it is definitely more visible with federal court cases Kind of bringing it to light policymakers bringing things more to light but the

05:51.234 --> 05:53.997
The simplest thing to know is that it impacts everyone.

05:54.637 --> 06:00.023
It's not just about housing and truly these numbers are growing.

06:01.524 --> 06:01.904
Thank you.

06:03.446 --> 06:05.548
So Christy, we'll go to you next.

06:06.429 --> 06:11.153
What are the biggest misconceptions that general public has about homelessness?

06:11.974 --> 06:20.082
I think that a lot of people believe that people who are homeless are lazy.

06:20.610 --> 06:28.918
And, you know, they're not working, but I'm gonna tell you that being homeless is hard, okay?

06:29.419 --> 06:38.047
There is so much trying to get around 98% of the people who are homeless do not have a working vehicle.

06:38.627 --> 06:43.973
So they are using bus transportation, going here, there.

06:44.453 --> 06:49.458
Sometimes it takes people two and a half hours on the bus to drop off a child

06:49.730 --> 06:51.373
actually get to a job.

06:53.837 --> 06:59.386
Also, I have so many employed people in the shelter.

07:00.087 --> 07:01.730
They're just underemployed.

07:01.750 --> 07:15.794
The cost of living downtown is such that it's very hard at $1,200 to $1,500 for a house, a two-bedroom house.

07:16.290 --> 07:18.493
It's very hard to sustain that.

07:19.053 --> 07:23.940
At the Dream Center, we work on building self-sustaining families.

07:24.020 --> 07:25.101
That's very important.

07:25.842 --> 07:29.867
We don't want to create something where a year later it's not going to work.

07:30.728 --> 07:36.375
So we work and get them someplace that they can long-term sustain.

07:38.157 --> 07:38.578
Thank you.

07:39.394 --> 07:43.259
OK, we're going to have a question for all of the panel now, and we'll start off with you, Andy, for this one.

07:43.279 --> 07:48.086
But what do you see as the most significant drivers of homelessness right now?

07:50.269 --> 07:51.390
Well, there's a few.

07:52.151 --> 07:55.395
Obviously, we just heard of economy, things like that.

07:55.896 --> 07:57.738
But I think it's a deeper root.

07:58.399 --> 08:06.730
I think there's a longing to be seen, to be heard, to be known, but also the longing for a father.

08:08.293 --> 08:09.394
And I'm talking about God.

08:10.146 --> 08:14.793
And I think that there's a longing in each and every one of us.

08:15.153 --> 08:29.954
And some of the things that we see and Christie touched on it, the majority of the people that we see at the Dream Center aren't the folks that you may see on TV or that are in the encampments.

08:30.134 --> 08:38.226
Our predominant person that comes into the Dream Center is a single parent mom with kids.

08:39.426 --> 08:44.853
It's a mom who has moved to Peoria for either a job or a boyfriend.

08:45.875 --> 08:51.863
And when they get to Peoria, one or both fall aside.

08:51.903 --> 08:55.087
They don't have the boyfriend or the job falls through.

08:55.147 --> 09:00.955
And because they've moved to Peoria, their network is not here.

09:02.237 --> 09:03.299
It's where they came from.

09:04.841 --> 09:08.786
And so that's where places like the Dream Center step in

09:09.826 --> 09:11.608
to become that network.

09:12.550 --> 09:26.529
And so having people, especially people of faith in that network is critical to be able to then direct them not only to the services and to housing, but also to Jesus.

09:26.870 --> 09:32.778
He is the ultimate answer to anyone's problems, including someone that's homeless.

09:32.798 --> 09:35.001
So I think that is a significant drive.

09:35.522 --> 09:36.924
Thank you.

09:36.944 --> 09:38.386
John, we'll go to you.

09:38.754 --> 09:42.297
Yeah, I think we've talked a little bit about the drivers.

09:42.438 --> 10:08.082
I think there's so Multifaceted it's complex There's never one answer I think I have a question coming up about what's a typical story and maybe I'll combine these a little bit and say that There isn't a typical These are individuals and and we have to look at them in that way, but I would say we see Kind of some common threads

10:08.546 --> 10:13.753
of what drive homelessness in these situations.

10:13.833 --> 10:17.999
And I kind of call them the AAA, if you can remember it that way.

10:18.579 --> 10:19.821
The first one is abuse.

10:21.463 --> 10:35.762
My guess is, Christine and Andy, if I asked you and Nicole too, we know that within our ministry, at least 90 to 95% of the women that we encounter have

10:35.842 --> 10:38.926
experienced abuse of some sort or another.

10:39.867 --> 10:47.037
And it's sometimes incredibly tragic, but it's just, it's very common.

10:47.237 --> 10:56.329
And even on the men's side, you'd be surprised how many of the men have suffered either physical or sexual abuse, and it's just tragic.

10:57.511 --> 10:58.452
The other is addiction.

10:58.973 --> 11:05.682
Addiction, you know, a lot of folks, I'm gonna say a lot of us manage our addictions,

11:05.858 --> 11:11.084
and can manage them, but sometimes addictions get out of control.

11:12.426 --> 11:14.849
And then they're ravaging.

11:15.350 --> 11:18.934
And when that happens, sometimes you lose everything.

11:19.615 --> 11:22.018
And so that's the second A.

11:22.038 --> 11:23.800
And then the third one is abandonment.

11:24.861 --> 11:27.564
And I use that term in a lot of different ways.

11:27.725 --> 11:28.626
Andy mentioned it.

11:29.587 --> 11:33.992
If you get here and you don't have a support system, you feel abandoned.

11:34.233 --> 11:35.474
Sometimes your family

11:35.746 --> 11:38.870
has to abandon you because of some things that are going on.

11:38.930 --> 11:42.435
And then our systems abandon people.

11:43.596 --> 11:45.599
Mental health is a big deal.

11:45.799 --> 11:52.448
And as a society, as a government, we haven't done well with supporting mental health.

11:52.949 --> 12:00.679
We need more residential mental health facilities to care for some folks who are really struggling with that.

12:00.699 --> 12:03.282
So again, not a real

12:03.394 --> 12:11.603
specific answer because a general answer in the sense that everybody's different but those three are big drivers that we see.

12:12.705 --> 12:15.107
Thank you Nicole.

12:15.428 --> 12:27.762
I think a lot and the reason I jumped from the nonprofit sector to city government is because a lot of what we're doing as nonprofits right there's amazing nonprofits and

12:27.938 --> 12:30.460
There's some amazing churches in this community, right?

12:30.500 --> 12:44.734
There's so many different players that are impacting this work, but if we don't fix the system that everyone is operating in, I mean, our goal probably unanimously across this panel would be to work ourselves out of a job, right?

12:44.994 --> 12:47.216
We don't have people experiencing homelessness.

12:48.117 --> 12:51.780
We have broken the chains of the AAA, right?

12:51.820 --> 12:57.906
That would be our ultimate goal, but until we actually fix the system that this operates in,

12:57.986 --> 13:01.050
we will never get any closer to achieving that.

13:01.370 --> 13:25.458
And so really, I see a lot of the drivers and how they impact individuals and families experiencing homelessness is because of those system failures, whether that's not making enough at work, whether that is not being able to access appropriate healthcare, whether that is an old home that needs so many repairs, that your Ammon bill costs more than your monthly rent as the rent is also going up.

13:25.794 --> 13:32.822
And so there are so many components that could bring someone in through the doors of Pathways or Dream Center.

13:33.323 --> 13:41.432
And if we don't fix the reasons as to why people are showing up in the first place, we will always need these systems of care.

13:41.993 --> 13:47.239
And truly, as disciples of Christ heard it, it is our job to care for one another.

13:47.259 --> 13:51.524
So I'm not saying, let's get rid of the nonprofits and make this a human thing, right?

13:51.864 --> 13:53.426
But it is a human thing too.

13:53.666 --> 14:04.661
So I would say the drivers are really sometimes the situations that are out of someone's control and what stop gaps are in place to help someone recover when something does happen in their life.

14:06.183 --> 14:06.523
Christy.

14:07.144 --> 14:23.506
Okay, I think everybody said pretty much everything but I do want to say last year we touched 1,300 women, children and families and of those 96%

14:24.322 --> 14:31.591
had trauma, domestic violence, sexual abuse in their backgrounds.

14:32.773 --> 14:38.580
So what we're saying is we have to get to the root of the problem before we can solve it.

14:41.224 --> 14:43.026
Yeah.

14:43.046 --> 14:43.326
OK.

14:43.807 --> 14:46.711
So another specific question for you, John.

14:46.771 --> 14:48.313
I know you answered this a little bit.

14:48.353 --> 14:50.015
I don't know if you want to add anything else to it.

14:50.075 --> 14:52.498
But when you think about the individuals you serve,

14:53.250 --> 15:00.298
What does the typical quote unquote typical story of someone becoming homeless look like if that exists?

15:00.318 --> 15:06.404
Yeah, and I think we would all say it's funny because we just mentioned some big numbers.

15:07.165 --> 15:10.489
You know, Christy talked about 1300, was it?

15:11.089 --> 15:17.977
And we see a couple thousand and it's honestly, there isn't a single story.

15:18.538 --> 15:22.642
And that's because what happens is, and I say this a lot,

15:23.234 --> 15:27.099
And Nicole touched on it some, but I wanna even deepen it a little bit.

15:27.279 --> 15:31.745
When do you think about homelessness or poverty as a problem?

15:32.966 --> 15:33.907
It's overwhelming.

15:34.488 --> 15:37.992
It seems unsolvable because then you get into this.

15:38.133 --> 15:41.337
It just seems, you can't even touch it.

15:42.138 --> 15:48.946
But when you think about it as a person, one person that we can come alongside and help, suddenly,

15:49.186 --> 15:52.790
That adds up to 1,300 people or thousands.

15:53.571 --> 16:00.739
But what you find is it's no longer sometimes you refer to folks as groups, right?

16:01.380 --> 16:03.242
Oh, we need to deal with the homeless.

16:04.043 --> 16:16.818
Well, that in and of itself is dehumanizing because it's actually Fred and it's Brian and it's Susie and it's, you know, it's a person.

16:17.314 --> 16:22.722
And we have to really focus it at a person level because that's where we can make the difference.

16:22.862 --> 16:26.287
And you know, we've all said all the different drivers in the end.

16:26.327 --> 16:27.469
I think Andy touched on it.

16:28.771 --> 16:32.897
Hopelessness is what is really the biggest driver.

16:33.117 --> 16:37.544
And these folks need the hope of Christ because he loves them.

16:38.345 --> 16:44.694
They're made in his image and we need to come along alongside of them and find out who their name is, what their story is.

16:44.774 --> 16:47.218
It's always, always different.

16:49.058 --> 16:51.701
OK, Andy, you have the question next.

16:51.781 --> 16:57.267
What does dignity look like in the context of homelessness services?

16:58.588 --> 17:06.457
I think if you look in scripture, you see Christ as our example for showing dignity.

17:07.998 --> 17:16.968
Whenever he was around people, yes, there was a lot of people around him, but he always showed the individual dignity.

17:17.028 --> 17:17.769
He saw them.

17:17.869 --> 17:18.770
He heard them.

17:19.970 --> 17:36.116
And it's so important because it changes your perspective of from driving past someone or walking past someone to actually having the eyes of Jesus to be able to then approach someone.

17:36.216 --> 17:39.402
And I know it can be scary at the Dream Center this week.

17:39.882 --> 17:46.994
There was a lady that I hadn't seen before and she

17:48.002 --> 17:52.408
was struggling in a lot of ways, mental illness, things like that.

17:53.089 --> 17:56.694
But just me stopping and saying, how you doing today?

17:56.914 --> 17:57.715
You doing okay?

17:58.036 --> 17:58.897
Can I pray for you?

18:01.640 --> 18:07.288
It didn't do anything to me, but it did everything to her because I showed her dignity.

18:08.390 --> 18:14.398
And for us at the Dream Center, we have three core values, dignity, compassion, and purpose.

18:14.418 --> 18:17.522
And dignity drives us to compassion.

18:18.530 --> 18:28.340
Once you see someone, hear someone, even for us, the way our staff and volunteers treat people, the way the building looks, the way the building sounds.

18:28.380 --> 18:32.564
If you come into the Dream Center, there is worship, music, playing, all throughout.

18:33.665 --> 18:42.694
Bringing that dignity to someone can then bring the walls down to then be able to show the love of Christ in real ways.

18:42.794 --> 18:46.418
So that's why dignity is a big deal.

18:46.818 --> 18:50.704
not just the dreams and I know pathway does it incredibly as well.

18:51.225 --> 18:57.814
You've got to see people, you've got to hear people and you've got to be able to present Jesus when them walls come down.

18:59.397 --> 18:59.757
Thank you.

19:01.360 --> 19:11.134
Okay, so we're going to take several minutes for each of these individuals to be able to answer a couple of questions.

19:13.117 --> 19:13.778
If one

19:14.370 --> 19:21.538
is more impactful for you to respond to, but I'll just read some of these questions that may help shape what you discuss next.

19:22.639 --> 19:26.803
What role can faith communities, nonprofits, and citizens play?

19:28.445 --> 19:33.030
What should people understand before volunteering or donating?

19:34.392 --> 19:38.416
What is one thing attendees should walk away understanding today?

19:38.496 --> 19:43.922
What practical action can individuals take this month

19:44.770 --> 19:51.540
And lastly, how can the community build a long-term culture of compassion and accountability?

19:54.224 --> 19:57.049
And so I'll just start off with you, Andy, and we'll move on down the line.

20:00.734 --> 20:13.714
The role of the faith community is critical because what you bring, the general public may not bring.

20:14.658 --> 20:20.164
And that's being salt and light to folks who are in a dark place.

20:22.627 --> 20:28.993
When you read in Matthew 9 and 10, Jesus is about to send out the disciples in Matthew 9.

20:29.013 --> 20:36.622
He is entering a city and his heart, it says his heart is turned to compassion.

20:36.682 --> 20:44.370
You have to be around people to feel that pull to be able to have compassion

20:44.930 --> 20:45.551
for people.

20:45.992 --> 20:49.217
And it really, really got to Jesus.

20:50.839 --> 20:52.802
And it says, the cries of the city.

20:52.842 --> 20:54.785
It talks about the cries of the city.

20:54.805 --> 20:58.772
I know I've mentioned this when I've been here before, but it's something we live and breathe.

20:58.832 --> 21:04.481
Here in the cries of the city is essential to be able to make a difference.

21:04.661 --> 21:10.450
And as you hear the cries of the city, you then go on to chapter

21:10.562 --> 21:15.288
10 in Matthew where Jesus is now sending out the disciples.

21:15.329 --> 21:18.613
He's sending them out and it's not just to do good.

21:21.116 --> 21:22.478
It's to help heal people.

21:22.558 --> 21:23.780
It's to listen.

21:24.141 --> 21:28.947
It's to be able to be alongside people in their time of need.

21:29.368 --> 21:36.818
And as a disciple, it's one of those things that we can't really get away from because Jesus lived it.

21:38.530 --> 21:47.520
And so for the faith community, what you have is crucial to people's lives that we're dealing with each and every day.

21:48.961 --> 21:51.043
Let me tell you a little story.

21:52.385 --> 21:59.312
Just a few months ago, you may remember there was a pause on some of the benefits that were happening.

22:01.735 --> 22:05.859
And for the crowd that we serve, that's a big deal, right?

22:05.960 --> 22:08.242
A lot of people were concerned about

22:08.354 --> 22:10.176
where food was going to come from.

22:11.318 --> 22:17.865
And so the Dream Center did a like a food drive similar to what we did during COVID.

22:18.787 --> 22:22.912
And we collected all this food and then we told the community come and get it.

22:22.932 --> 22:27.757
It was over a thousand packages of food that we had ready for families that were struggling.

22:28.598 --> 22:30.841
And this gal shows up to volunteer.

22:32.403 --> 22:38.290
I recognised her a little bit, but she was busy getting stuff and then she

22:39.362 --> 22:44.530
She asked one of our workers if she could go in the building, because we were doing this outside.

22:44.550 --> 22:48.916
This gal was about 15, 16, something like that.

22:49.357 --> 22:51.159
So one of our workers took her in the building.

22:51.179 --> 23:00.473
And this gal starts asking real poignant questions and asking for certain places in the building to go and look at.

23:02.115 --> 23:06.642
Our worker felt it was strange, but we're like, yeah, we'll go with it.

23:06.818 --> 23:09.722
She's taking this young gal around, goes to the gym.

23:09.762 --> 23:12.686
She has to go down one of the back hallways, which was weird.

23:13.186 --> 23:14.989
Then she has to go in the youth area.

23:15.490 --> 23:19.094
And then she gets to the bottom of the stairs at the Dream Center.

23:19.114 --> 23:27.105
And if you've been to the Dream Center, we have these huge images of all different people that have been through the Dream Center.

23:27.125 --> 23:28.707
So our work is said to this girl.

23:28.727 --> 23:32.893
I've got to ask you, why are you wanting to go to all these different places?

23:32.933 --> 23:36.818
Like, not many people know about the back hallway and the gym.

23:39.170 --> 23:46.581
She said, four years ago, I walked into this building with my dad, and we were both homeless.

23:48.744 --> 23:51.909
She said, I lived here for two years with my dad.

23:53.231 --> 24:03.807
And during that time, my dad got help and got a job, and she became part of our after-school programs that we have every day.

24:03.867 --> 24:06.130
And our main

24:06.402 --> 24:11.852
focus is to impact families living in poverty, starting with kids and youth.

24:13.354 --> 24:31.506
So we were able to take this gal who was homeless, bring her into the after school program, she got involved, had a wonderful time and the reason why she was wanting to go to the different areas was because it was different areas where her life had been impacted

24:32.514 --> 24:39.843
She remembers walking with volunteers down the back hallway to skip the crowds to be able to get to the youth area.

24:40.143 --> 24:42.827
She remembers playing ball in the gym.

24:42.887 --> 24:46.351
She remembered doing Bible study in the youth area.

24:47.112 --> 24:50.156
And as the worker was listening to this, she was a new worker.

24:50.196 --> 24:51.978
She hadn't not met this gal before.

24:52.538 --> 24:54.341
She couldn't believe what she was hearing.

24:55.482 --> 25:01.970
And like I said, they were standing at the bottom of the stairwell and she turned to the worker

25:02.146 --> 25:04.008
And she said, you see this picture?

25:04.048 --> 25:06.411
She said, yes, she said, that's me.

25:08.273 --> 25:10.655
And it was a picture we had taken four years ago.

25:10.675 --> 25:15.580
I mentioned all of that because what you do matters.

25:16.682 --> 25:19.104
It wasn't just workers that helped that gal.

25:19.605 --> 25:20.686
It was volunteers.

25:20.766 --> 25:22.748
It was churches coming alongside.

25:23.249 --> 25:25.671
It was pastors coming in and doing devotions.

25:27.213 --> 25:32.018
And now, she is planning on graduating high school

25:32.546 --> 25:41.576
She's told us that she wants to go and become a social worker so she can come and work at the Dream Center because of what it did to her.

25:41.976 --> 25:58.514
That is what's so critical about people like you and in faith groups, in churches, being able to make a difference because you have the light and you have the soul to be able to make a difference in someone's life.

26:01.378 --> 26:03.320
It's hard to follow that beautiful story.

26:03.461 --> 26:03.741
It is.

26:03.821 --> 26:09.568
But you're going to probably feel like you're getting piled up on because I'm going to tell you the church is the key.

26:10.749 --> 26:11.690
The church is the key.

26:14.073 --> 26:19.500
We love Nicole, actually, and the work that the city has done is pretty significant for a city.

26:19.640 --> 26:21.102
They are really trying to step in.

26:22.023 --> 26:24.466
But government can't solve this problem.

26:24.846 --> 26:25.347
They can't.

26:25.868 --> 26:29.973
I love it that they can try to address the systems.

26:30.033 --> 26:31.154
That's really important.

26:31.330 --> 26:34.514
but it's the people that we have to touch and the church is truly the key.

26:34.694 --> 26:45.107
And if you look at, all you have to do is Google kind of homelessness and the government's response and the last, and you're gonna see that the dollars keep going up and the problem keeps going up.

26:45.127 --> 26:47.270
So something's not quite right there.

26:47.350 --> 26:53.938
And it's because we believe that poverty is not about a lack of material things.

26:54.434 --> 27:22.994
Poverty is the brokenness that we all experience in the four fundamental relationships of life our relationship with God our relationship with ourself our relationship with others and our relationship with the rest of creation or work and So that's just something that the church and the gospel can step into in a way that government just never could or just wasn't designed to do so it's the church is the key and you know, I will tell you that

27:23.490 --> 27:25.032
The Bible is quite clear.

27:25.092 --> 27:29.657
Deuteronomy 15, take some time and look at that.

27:29.817 --> 27:32.700
Isaiah 58, take some time and look at that.

27:32.860 --> 27:48.197
And God designed His people to step into this because of the nature of what poverty is, if it's broken relationships, starting first and foremost with God, then it's going to be the church that really can make the impact on this.

27:48.317 --> 27:53.042
So we talk about some practical ways to step in.

27:53.378 --> 28:02.712
It's estimated there's about 30,000 folks that identify as Protestant believers here in pure area.

28:04.274 --> 28:06.257
I think I can ask Andy pretty safely.

28:06.798 --> 28:07.960
We don't have that many donors.

28:10.243 --> 28:11.846
We don't have a half of them.

28:11.866 --> 28:13.048
I mean, we don't have clothes.

28:14.029 --> 28:17.434
So I'm going to just say, step in a little bit.

28:18.416 --> 28:20.018
Give a little bit.

28:20.322 --> 28:29.552
It doesn't have to be, we know it could be a sacrifice, but you're actually doing what Christ would want us to do, step in.

28:30.393 --> 28:33.936
And then here's something really, I like this idea.

28:34.177 --> 28:46.930
If you're shopping, if you're going to the grocery store and we all know prices are up and everything's crazy, well we all use some of those things that you're buying, milk, eggs,

28:47.330 --> 28:47.991
We get a lot.

28:48.011 --> 28:52.818
We all get a lot of donations, but some of the staple items, we don't.

28:53.640 --> 28:55.162
That's just not available to us.

28:55.763 --> 29:02.313
So if you're buying for your groceries for that week, take your kids along and make two lists.

29:02.774 --> 29:09.043
Make our list and a list for Dream Center or a list for Pathway and bring a gallon of milk.

29:09.264 --> 29:13.490
If 50 people bought a gallon of milk each week,

29:14.082 --> 29:17.586
It'd be amazing for what we could do and what we could do.

29:17.646 --> 29:24.713
So those are just some practical ways that you could step in and actually make a difference.

29:25.934 --> 29:28.497
And of course, yeah, consider volunteering.

29:29.478 --> 29:34.943
Amber mentioned that she's stepped in to pathway ministries and doing life skill classes.

29:35.003 --> 29:41.650
So if you have a particular area that you have experience in, wisdom in,

29:41.826 --> 29:47.092
Man, those are great opportunities to step in and do something direct and meaningful.

29:51.377 --> 29:54.100
I love when you started this, right?

29:54.341 --> 29:58.846
And what was spoken last week about proximity brings to empathy.

29:59.667 --> 30:02.450
Because I truly believe it's hard to hate up close.

30:03.772 --> 30:09.298
When I was 10, I had the opportunity to go to Russia with my mom with a group called Children's Hope Chest.

30:09.666 --> 30:16.374
And we were serving in the orphanages and running kind of like a winter camp, if you will, think about summer in the winter time.

30:17.476 --> 30:19.458
These are kids that didn't speak the same language as me.

30:20.420 --> 30:21.681
But I knew they were different than me.

30:21.981 --> 30:26.127
And it was a difference in what they didn't have and what I did.

30:26.928 --> 30:33.896
And so that brought me into social work and determining that kind of housing was the path to go.

30:34.998 --> 30:38.322
But I say that to say that, again, if you're

30:38.594 --> 30:41.818
getting to know the stories behind what's happening, right?

30:41.878 --> 30:44.141
Like, there are issues in the system.

30:44.221 --> 30:45.943
There are issues in policy.

30:46.584 --> 30:48.927
And those are really big things.

30:49.908 --> 30:52.792
But this is truly a human issue.

30:53.373 --> 30:55.976
And this is truly our brothers and sisters.

30:56.637 --> 31:03.666
And if you get to know their stories through volunteering, it will truly change your heart

31:03.842 --> 31:11.373
and it will change some of the stereotypes that we all carry, whether we know that we carry them or whether we don't necessarily recognize that we do.

31:13.436 --> 31:16.921
So to me, I think our Peoria is really blessed.

31:17.402 --> 31:19.465
We have an amazing nonprofit community.

31:20.567 --> 31:22.930
The church is also extremely blessed, right?

31:22.950 --> 31:24.432
Times, talents, and treasures.

31:26.015 --> 31:33.746
There are a lot of creative solutions that churches have brought, if you Google that,

31:33.858 --> 31:36.882
You will see churches paying off people's medical debt.

31:36.902 --> 31:43.892
You will see churches popping up tiny homes in their parking lot or creating a safe parking lot for people who are sleeping in their cars to stay in.

31:44.232 --> 31:48.838
There are so many things you can do no matter what your age, no matter what your abilities.

31:49.599 --> 31:56.990
And so I think finding a way to plug in, you don't have to figure out how to solve this yourself, right?

31:57.210 --> 32:03.218
If you already bring that you are the hands and feet of Jesus in every space that you go into,

32:03.778 --> 32:09.966
These nonprofits have a great pulse on the problem and they also have a great pulse on the people and open doors.

32:10.647 --> 32:20.099
They will help guide the actions that you're curious about and the ways that you can get involved so you don't necessarily have to figure out a way to solve this yourself.

32:20.599 --> 32:28.850
Look to those who are doing really good work like the people you see on this panel, see what they're asking for, see what their needs are and do that.

32:29.282 --> 32:32.046
They are truly asking for the things that they need.

32:32.066 --> 32:33.749
This is not access, right?

32:33.989 --> 32:37.114
There is a scarcity mindset, but there really truly is plenty.

32:38.176 --> 32:52.178
And so if we can remember that there is plenty and that the actions of many can truly make things happen, that is the tangible you can walk away with is that there is literally something that every single person can do.

32:52.322 --> 32:54.766
And you may not get to see your impact directly.

32:55.106 --> 33:00.114
Sometimes there's really cool experiences where you genuinely do see your impact directly at the time you're doing it.

33:00.394 --> 33:09.347
But sometimes it's stories like the one Andy told, right, where that 16 year old was just like a 16 year old sitting out here and we wouldn't know their story unless she had been willing to share it.

33:10.369 --> 33:13.874
So I think there's just a place for everyone to get involved.

33:14.178 --> 33:18.844
but I think a really big thing if you're thinking about what you can do this month, that's really tangible, a low-hanging fruit.

33:19.185 --> 33:20.246
Find a good book to read.

33:20.306 --> 33:26.915
There's all kinds of books whether you're interested in the policy side of things or you do want to know more about the stories.

33:27.776 --> 33:36.968
They will help you connect with what's happening and truly see that there is a place that doesn't, there's really not a whole lot of difference in any single one of us, right?

33:37.729 --> 33:41.554
Whether it's the privilege that allows us all to sit in this room today

33:41.698 --> 33:45.222
or the folks that are at the Dream Center are literally right now.

33:45.242 --> 33:46.804
We're at Pathways literally right now.

33:49.667 --> 33:55.013
Okay, well I guess I get to finish up, but I'm gonna make this short and sweet.

33:56.335 --> 34:03.984
I believe that we exist so that others can know the love and salvation of Jesus Christ.

34:05.686 --> 34:09.330
Jesus calls us to love God and to love our neighbors.

34:09.666 --> 34:18.118
For us, that means showing up for the homeless, the addicted, the mentally ill, the broken, the lost, and the forgotten.

34:18.138 --> 34:20.902
That's who Jesus came for.

34:20.942 --> 34:23.686
And that's who we serve every day.

34:23.726 --> 34:27.291
He is calling us to serve.

34:27.391 --> 34:28.973
He is calling you to serve.

34:29.775 --> 34:37.906
We would love to have you come beside us, walk beside us, whether that's volunteerism, donation,

34:38.370 --> 34:39.892
Just praying for us.

34:41.976 --> 34:43.578
You have an open invitation.

34:43.598 --> 34:46.362
I'm sure you do it pathways as well.

34:48.005 --> 34:53.894
Thank you for having us today and I really hope that we get the chance to work with all of you.

35:05.231 --> 35:07.154
So there's research that shows

35:08.226 --> 35:20.218
that when someone has something that's really impactful happened to them and they feel this calling to help out, that if they don't make plans to actually do that within two weeks, that it never happens.

35:22.360 --> 35:36.114
And so our ask for you today is to take a moment before the band plays and to just consider what it would look like for you to come alongside

35:36.482 --> 35:51.385
Either these organizations or others in the Peoria area to use your time, talents, money, prayers to be able to step in and help this vulnerable population to be able to make a difference.

35:52.246 --> 36:01.280
We heard from this panel today that the churches are where it's probably going to be most impactful because we don't have enough dollars in the city to make that much of a difference as we'd like.

36:01.881 --> 36:05.266
So take a moment and what can you do

36:05.474 --> 36:13.682
for you, for your family to be able to come alongside each of these individuals and the organizations they represent to be able to make a difference for the city of Peoria.

